{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"1713","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:31 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Traditional grammars refer to this marker as <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f56\u0fb2\u0f7a\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f66\u0f92\u0fb2\u0f0b<\/span>, literally \u201clink sound,\u201d \u201crelation sound,\u201d and it is commonly translated by the English \u201cof.\u201d<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The genitive has several variant forms depending on the final letter of the preceding word. These variants are: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span><\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span> is used after a vowel and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>, and the <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0fb2\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span> is used after <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In Classical Tibetan, vowels and the letter <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span> may be followed by the variant <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f61\u0f72\u0f0b<\/span>; this is especially true in poetry, to suit the requirements of the meter.<\/p><p class=\"Paragraph\">The genitive is used not only to form noun complements, possessive pronouns, and adjectives, but also relative clauses. In this case, it may be translated by a relative pronoun such as \u201cthat,\u201d \u201cwho,\u201d \u201cwhere,\u201d etc. The complement that is marked by the genitive always precedes the noun to which it refers.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cMy friend\u201d (Literally: \u201cThe friend of me\u201d) <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f41\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f55\u0fb1\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f66\u0fa8\u0fb1\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cHis pen\u201d (Literally: \u201cThe pen of him\u201d) <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f40\u0fb2\u0f0b\u0f64\u0f72\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f40\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f74\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTrashi\u2019s son\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0fb3\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f66\u0fb3\u0fb3\u0f7c\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cThe lama\u2019s disciple\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f42\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f56\u0fb1\u0f7a\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cGovernment civil servant\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f42\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f92\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f42\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cThe teacher\u2019s book\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cThe photo that\u2019s in the book\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In the literary language the genitive case may also correspond to the conjunction \u201cbut.\u201d<\/p>","title":""}]}